{% extends "_base.j2" %}
{% block main %}
<span class="eyebrow">Learn · Operator runbook</span>
<h1>Operator runbook</h1>
<p class="page-hero">Deploy, day-2 operations, troubleshooting recipes, backup / restore, and health monitoring. The reader-facing version of <code>agent/research/operator-runbook.md</code>; updated as gotchas surface.</p>

<hr class="hairline">

<section>
  <header><span class="eyebrow">Step 1</span><h2>Deploy</h2></header>
  <h3>Recommended: Docker</h3>
  <p>The release bundle ships with a turnkey installer. From an unpacked <code>dwarf-release-v1/</code>:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cd dwarf-release-v1/
./scripts/install.sh
docker compose up -d</code></pre>
  <p>The installer pulls <code>dwarf/framework</code>, mounts <code>runs/</code>, <code>state/</code>, <code>bundles/</code> from the host into the container, and starts the dashboard at <a href="http://127.0.0.1:8787/operate"><code>http://127.0.0.1:8787/operate</code></a>. Prerequisites (Docker, docker-compose, ~10 GB free disk, ~4 GB RAM) are listed in <code>dwarf-release-v1/README.md</code>.</p>
  <h3>Alternative: bare metal</h3>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>git clone https://github.com/dwarf-fw/dwarf
cd dwarf
./scripts/setup.sh
./cardano-profile dashboard serve --bind 0.0.0.0 --port 8787</code></pre>
  <p>Same CLI, framework runs as host processes via tmux. <code>state/</code> · <code>runs/</code> · <code>bundles/</code> live under the repo root.</p>
</section>

<hr class="hairline">

<section>
  <header><span class="eyebrow">Step 2</span><h2>Common operations</h2></header>

  <h3>Run a scenario</h3>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code># Inside Docker
docker compose exec dwarf-fw \
  cardano-profile scenario run \
  scenarios/runtime-substrate-honest-baseline-example-smoke.yaml

# Bare metal
./cardano-profile scenario run \
  dwarf/scenarios/runtime-substrate-honest-baseline-example-smoke.yaml</code></pre>
  <p>Output lands in <code>runs/&lt;timestamp&gt;-&lt;hash&gt;/</code>; the dashboard auto-discovers it. <a href="/operate/runs">/operate/runs</a> lists newest-first.</p>

  <h3>View runs &amp; bundles</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/operate/runs">/operate/runs</a> — every run on disk, filterable by outcome / scenario / target.</li>
    <li><a href="/operate/runs/&lt;id&gt;">/operate/runs/&lt;id&gt;</a> — bundle inspector: manifest, hash chain, substrate evidence tiles, assertions, log tail.</li>
    <li><a href="/operate/runs/&lt;id&gt;/live">/operate/runs/&lt;id&gt;/live</a> — SSE log tail, useful while a scenario is running.</li>
    <li><a href="/operate/bundles">/operate/bundles</a> — preserved tar.gz archives + import upload form.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Export a bundle for an audit package</h3>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile bundle export &lt;run-id&gt;</code></pre>
  <p>Or click <strong>Export bundle (.tar.gz)</strong> on the inspector header. The framework verifies the manifest hash chain on its way out so the archive is tamper-proof at unpack time.</p>

  <h3>Import a bundle from another box</h3>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile bundle import &lt;path-to.tar.gz&gt;</code></pre>
  <p>Or drag-drop a tar.gz onto the upload form on <a href="/operate/bundles">/operate/bundles</a>. Existing run-ids are not overwritten.</p>

  <h3>Configure notifications</h3>
  <p>Edit <code>state/config.yaml</code>:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>notifications:
  on_scenario_fail:
    - type: webhook
      url: https://example.com/dwarf-hook
    - type: slack
      url: https://hooks.slack.com/services/T0/B0/XXXX
  on_coverage_regression:
    - type: email
      to: ops@example.com
  smtp:
    host: smtp.example.com
    port: 587
    from: dwarf@example.com</code></pre>
  <p>Restart the dashboard so the new config is read. Outcomes append to <code>state/notifications.log</code>. View configured rules at <a href="/operate/notifications">/operate/notifications</a>.</p>
</section>

<hr class="hairline">

<section>
  <header><span class="eyebrow">Step 3</span><h2 id="moog-security-testing">Moog security testing</h2></header>
  <p>Use this path when Dwarf-generated security test assets need to be submitted through Moog on Cardano Preprod. The dashboard wallet panel on <a href="/operate/status">/operate/status</a> is public telemetry only: requester id, address, tADA balance, health state, and recent transactions.</p>

  <h3>Connected requester wallet</h3>
  <p>The current requester wallet registered in Dwarf is <code>moog-requester</code> on Preprod:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>addr_test1vrwe82a7yv5nfxza7sy3c2z7n59556st005erdns5vxncucp94k9p</code></pre>
  <p>Check it from the CLI before starting a Moog workflow:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile wallet list
cardano-profile wallet healthcheck moog-requester
cardano-profile wallet healthcheck moog-requester --json
cardano-profile wallet test moog-requester --json</code></pre>
  <p>Use <code>--json</code> for automation because it suppresses the interactive Dwarf banner and leaves stdout as machine-readable JSON.</p>

  <h3>Moog deployment health</h3>
  <p>Dwarf can now check the Moog deployment on <code>cardano-box</code> without reading wallet secrets. The status checks verify the Moog binary, deploy directories, public requester/oracle metadata, Preprod MPFS/token configuration, and the <code>moog-oracle.service</code> systemd user unit state.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog config
cardano-profile moog config --json
cardano-profile moog status
cardano-profile moog status --json
cardano-profile moog healthcheck --json
cardano-profile moog status --dry-run</code></pre>
  <p>The dashboard surfaces the same data on <a href="/operate/status">/operate/status</a> under <strong>Moog · Deployment health</strong>. A warning state is expected while the oracle unit is intentionally disabled or inactive.</p>

  <h3>Dashboard setup form</h3>
  <p>Use <a href="/operate/config">/operate/config</a> before the client meeting to enter Moog, GitHub, target repository, and Antithesis values from the browser. The form reads effective values from Docker environment variables first, then saved Dwarf config. Environment variables can be supplied from the package <code>.env</code> file when the dashboard container starts.</p>
  <p>For the current client-prep mode, the form can save GitHub PATs, Antithesis passwords/API keys, and agent email passwords into the Dwarf <code>moog</code> config block. Secret fields are masked after save; leave them blank to preserve the existing saved value.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>MOOG_GITHUB_USER=&lt;real-github-user&gt;
MOOG_GITHUB_REPO=&lt;org/repo&gt;
MOOG_GITHUB_PAT=&lt;github-pat&gt;
MOOG_TARGET_DIRECTORY=&lt;repo-relative-test-dir&gt;
MOOG_TARGET_COMMIT=&lt;sha&gt;
MOOG_ANTITHESIS_LAUNCH_URL=https://amaru-cardano.antithesis.com/api/v1/launch/amaru-cardano
MOOG_ANTITHESIS_USER=pragma
MOOG_ANTITHESIS_PASSWORD=&lt;password&gt;
MOOG_REGISTRY=us-central1-docker.pkg.dev/molten-verve-216720/cardano-repository</code></pre>

  <h3>Opt-in Moog bootstrap</h3>
  <p>Dwarf delivery does not set up Moog by default. The deploy script has an explicit opt-in hook for operators who want Dwarf to prepare the safe Moog host skeleton from inside the running dashboard container.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code># Plan only; no remote state change.
DWARF_MOOG_BOOTSTRAP=plan bash delivery/scripts/deploy.sh

# Apply the safe skeleton; requires both variables.
DWARF_MOOG_BOOTSTRAP=approve \
DWARF_MOOG_BOOTSTRAP_APPROVE=1 \
bash delivery/scripts/deploy.sh</code></pre>
  <p>The approved path creates <code>deploy_root</code>, <code>deploy_root/ops</code>, <code>deploy_root/state</code>, <code>secrets_root</code>, <code>secrets_root/requester</code>, and <code>secrets_root/oracle</code>, then writes <code>deploy_root/ops/dwarf-moog-bootstrap-plan.txt</code>. It does not download binaries, create wallet files, read wallet JSON, store PATs, write Antithesis credentials, enable services, or start oracle/agent processes.</p>
  <p>Run the healthcheck sequence after any approved bootstrap or manual Moog change:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog bootstrap --json
cardano-profile moog bootstrap --approve --json
cardano-profile moog healthcheck --json
cardano-profile wallet healthcheck moog-requester --json
cardano-profile moog readiness --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; --github-user &lt;real-github-user&gt; --json
cardano-profile moog preflight --asset-dir &lt;dir&gt; --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; --github-user &lt;real-github-user&gt; --directory &lt;path&gt; --commit &lt;sha&gt; --json</code></pre>

  <h3>Moog non-secret config</h3>
  <p>The Moog config block is safe for public deployment metadata only. Set or replace it with a JSON object like this:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog set '{
  "enabled": true,
  "deploy_root": "/home/nigel/moog-deploy",
  "moog_binary": "/home/nigel/bin/moog",
  "secrets_root": "/home/nigel/moog-secrets",
  "mpfs_host": "https://mpfs.plutimus.com",
  "token_id": "21c523c3b4565f1fc1ad7e54e82ca976f60997d8e7e9946826813fabf341069b",
  "requester_wallet_id": "moog-requester",
  "oracle_service": "moog-oracle.service"
}'</code></pre>
  <p>Client-prep mode currently allows secrets in this block. Treat the resulting config file as private: do not commit it, copy it into workbench notes, or paste it into transcripts.</p>

  <h3>Add, replace, or remove wallet metadata</h3>
  <p>Dwarf stores public wallet metadata only. Use these commands when rotating the requester address or testing another Preprod wallet:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile wallet add moog-requester \
  --label "Moog requester" \
  --role requester \
  --network preprod \
  --address addr_test1vrwe82a7yv5nfxza7sy3c2z7n59556st005erdns5vxncucp94k9p

cardano-profile wallet remove moog-requester</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Do not store wallet mnemonics or private keys</strong> in dashboard config, repository files, command history, or workbench notes. GitHub PATs and Antithesis credentials may be saved through the Moog setup form for client-prep mode, but treat the Dwarf config file as private.</p>

  <h3>Preprod faucet handling</h3>
  <p>Use the public Cardano Preprod faucet when the requester wallet needs more test ada. Select <strong>Environment: Preprod Testnet</strong> and <strong>Action: Receive test ADA</strong>. Do not choose pool delegation for this requester flow.</p>
  <p>When testing is finished, return unused Preprod tADA to the Preprod faucet return address:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>addr_test1vzpwq95z3xyum8vqndgdd9mdnmafh3djcxnc6jemlgdmswcve6tkw</code></pre>

  <h3>Required user inputs before submission</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>A GitHub PAT with enough repository and organization visibility for the target workflow. Moog documentation calls for <code>repo</code> scope.</li>
    <li>A root <code>moog.vkey</code> file in the GitHub profile repository containing the requester wallet public key.</li>
    <li>Moog requester user registration for the GitHub account.</li>
    <li><code>antithesis: @&lt;github-user&gt;</code> in the target repository <code>CODEOWNERS</code> (root, <code>.github/</code>, or <code>docs/</code>). <strong>The username must be lowercase</strong> — the <code>moog</code> binary case-folds the username then compares it case-sensitively to the file, so <code>@J-GainSec</code> fails but <code>@j-gainsec</code> passes. (Note: Dwarf&rsquo;s own <code>moog readiness</code> check is case-insensitive and will report OK either way — the <code>moog</code> binary is the source of truth.)</li>
    <li>Repository role registration and Moog agent whitelist approval for the target repository.</li>
    <li>Dwarf security test assets committed to the target repository.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Register the requester user and repo role</h3>
  <p>Once <code>moog.vkey</code> is published and <code>CODEOWNERS</code> has the lowercase line, register on-chain. Dry-run first to see the exact commands, then submit (these are real Preprod transactions that spend a little tADA):</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code># Read-only: shows the register-user / register-role commands, no submission
cardano-profile moog registration-submit --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; --github-user &lt;user&gt; --dry-run --json</code></pre>
  <p>The underlying <code>moog</code> binary needs both a GitHub token and the wallet passphrase in its environment (source the passphrase from its <code>0600</code> file; never print it):</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>export MOOG_GITHUB_PAT=&lt;token&gt;
export MOOG_WALLET_PASSPHRASE="$(cat &lt;secrets&gt;/requester/wallet.passphrase)"
moog requester register-user  -w &lt;secrets&gt;/requester/requester.json -p github -u &lt;user&gt; -v &lt;requester-vkey&gt;
moog requester register-role  -w &lt;secrets&gt;/requester/requester.json -p github -r &lt;org/repo&gt; -u &lt;user&gt;</code></pre>
  <p>After both confirm (one Preprod block), <code>moog readiness</code> shows <code>moog_user_registered</code> and <code>moog_role_registered</code> as OK. The repository <strong>whitelist</strong> remains the Moog agent operator&rsquo;s action and stays a warning until they grant it.</p>

  <h3>Prepare local test assets without live submission</h3>
  <p>Use the asset helpers before the target repository is finalized. They only create and inspect local files; they do not contact GitHub, submit to Moog, launch Antithesis, or prove the workload is target-correct.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog asset scaffold --to /tmp/moog-asset --json
cardano-profile moog asset validate --asset-dir /tmp/moog-asset --json</code></pre>
  <p>The scaffold creates a minimal <code>docker-compose.yaml</code> and <code>README.md</code>. Replace the placeholder workload with the target-specific Dwarf security test services before any live Moog request.</p>

  <h3 id="antithesis-bundles">Build the Antithesis test bundle</h3>
  <p>Dwarf renders one profile definition to two execution backends: the local devnet (unchanged) and Antithesis. The <code>antithesis build</code> command is the real bundle generator that replaces the placeholder scaffold above. The workload container acts as the node&rsquo;s peer — it dials the Amaru node, drives fuzzed CBOR, and emits Antithesis SDK assertions (no-crash, liveness, clean-reject) — so the system is fully self-contained and hermetic.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile antithesis build profile-l-amaru-closed-devnet \
  --out antithesis/amaru-single \
  --json</code></pre>
  <p>The bundle writes <code>config/docker-compose.yaml</code> (registry images, <code>platform: linux/amd64</code>, <code>init: true</code>, healthchecks), <code>setup-complete.sh</code>, <code>test/parallel_driver.sh</code>, and a README. Validate it with the same asset tooling and confirm the compose resolves:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog asset validate --asset-dir antithesis/amaru-single --json
docker compose -f antithesis/amaru-single/config/docker-compose.yaml config</code></pre>
  <p>Building and validating a bundle submits nothing and launches nothing. The live run still requires the registration inputs above, the node and workload images pushed to the Antithesis registry, and the bundle committed to the target repository at a commit.</p>

  <h3>Mixed Haskell+Amaru devnet (cross-implementation differential)</h3>
  <p>The same emitter renders a mixed closed devnet from a mixed profile. The bundle then runs a Haskell <code>cardano-node</code> alongside Amaru, and the workload drives the <strong>same fuzzed CBOR at both</strong> — asserting they <strong>agree</strong> (both accept or both cleanly reject; neither panics) on top of the per-node invariants. This is the cross-implementation differential signal.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile antithesis build profile-c-mixed-haskell-amaru-minimal \
  --out antithesis/mixed-haskell-amaru \
  --json</code></pre>
  <p>The mixed bundle emits <code>cardano-node-1</code> + <code>amaru-1</code> + <code>workload</code>, sets <code>WORKLOAD_TARGETS</code> to both nodes, and runs the <code>drive-differential</code> test command. The Haskell node boots hermetically from a devnet env baked into a <code>cardano-node-devnet</code> image; build and push that image (plus <code>amaru</code> and the workload) before a live run:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code># Generate the devnet env and bake the image (uses cardano-testnet on the host):
bash dwarf/antithesis_devnet/build.sh &lt;registry&gt; &lt;tag&gt;
cardano-profile moog asset validate --asset-dir antithesis/mixed-haskell-amaru --json
docker compose -f antithesis/mixed-haskell-amaru/config/docker-compose.yaml config</code></pre>

  <h3>Plan the create-test request</h3>
  <p>Once the real target fields are known, generate the command Dwarf would use later. This remains dry-run planning and will report missing repo/user/directory/commit fields as blockers instead of inventing values.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog create-test-plan \
  --asset-dir /tmp/moog-asset \
  --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; \
  --github-user &lt;real-github-user&gt; \
  --directory &lt;repo-relative-test-dir&gt; \
  --commit &lt;sha&gt; \
  --json</code></pre>

  <h3>Run combined preflight</h3>
  <p>Use preflight as the single readiness view before a future live request. It combines Moog deployment health, requester readiness, local asset validation, and create-test command planning. A <code>blocked</code> result means at least one stage still needs operator input.</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code>cardano-profile moog preflight \
  --asset-dir /tmp/moog-asset \
  --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; \
  --github-user &lt;real-github-user&gt; \
  --directory &lt;repo-relative-test-dir&gt; \
  --commit &lt;sha&gt; \
  --json</code></pre>

  <p>After those inputs are ready and preflight is no longer blocked, submit through Moog with the guarded live path chosen by the operator. Do not run live <code>moog requester create-test</code> or Antithesis launch/report ingestion until credentials and Antithesis readiness are confirmed.</p>

  <h3 id="live-run">Submit a live run (Moog create-test)</h3>
  <p>The launch is a Moog <code>create-test</code> transaction — <strong>not</strong> a direct Antithesis API call, and it needs no Antithesis launch credentials. You submit it as the registered requester; the oracle validates registration + whitelist, then the Cardano Foundation agent launches it on the <code>amaru-cardano</code> Antithesis tenant. Dwarf wraps it:</p>
  <pre class="run-payload-pre"><code># Dry-run prints the exact moog requester create-test command:
cardano-profile moog create-test --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; --github-user &lt;user&gt; \
  --directory antithesis/cardano_node_dwarf --commit &lt;sha&gt; --no-faults --json

# Live submit (on-chain; spends a little Preprod tADA). 1-hour duration per CF guidance:
cardano-profile moog create-test --repo &lt;org/repo&gt; --github-user &lt;user&gt; \
  --directory antithesis/cardano_node_dwarf --commit &lt;sha&gt; --duration 1 --no-faults --approve --json

# Poll the Moog-side phase (full findings/triage are in the Antithesis dashboard):
cardano-profile moog test-status &lt;test-run-id&gt; --json</code></pre>
  <p>Phase progresses <code>pending → accepted → terminal</code>. The wallet passphrase and GitHub PAT are sourced from their on-host files at submit time and never logged. The <code>--try</code> number auto-increments per (commit, directory, repository, requester); a first run is <code>1</code>. Run a <code>--no-faults</code> smoke first, then drop the flag for the fault-injection run.</p>

  <h3>What Antithesis does vs. what Dwarf provides</h3>
  <p>A common point of confusion: Antithesis already &ldquo;exercises everything,&rdquo; so why inject anything? The division of labor:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Antithesis (the platform, automatic):</strong> controls all nondeterminism (scheduling, timing, randomness), injects <em>infrastructure</em> faults (network partitions, message drop/reorder, container kill/pause/restart, clock skew), searches the state space for assertion violations, and makes any finding deterministically reproducible. You do not write this.</li>
    <li><strong>Dwarf / the components (you provide):</strong> the <em>workload</em> and the <em>assertions</em>. Antithesis injects infrastructure faults but does <strong>not</strong> craft <em>protocol-level adversarial payloads</em> (e.g. malformed CBOR over node-to-node). Something must generate that traffic — that is the role of an adversary/fuzz component.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The synergy: a fuzz component seeds its mutation choices from <code>antithesis_random</code>, handing the steering wheel to Antithesis&rsquo;s search — turning random fuzzing into guided exploration of the malformed-input space combined with concurrent infrastructure faults. CF&rsquo;s stock components cover valid load (<code>tx-generator</code>), app activity (<code>asteria-game</code>), and behavioral misbehavior (<code>adversary</code>); a Dwarf CBOR-fuzz component adds the serialization/deserialization dimension none of them cover.</p>
</section>

